		<body>
			<div type="month" mhs:startingPage="322"  mhs:precedingFile="JQADiaries-v24-1801-03-p319.xml" mhs:followingFile="JQADiaries-v24-1801-05-p324.xml" mhs:volume="24">
				<bibl n="metadata"><date from="1801-04-01" to="1801-04-30"/></bibl>

				<!--D/JQA/24.2429-->
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-01">
					<head>1 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-01"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<dateline><hi rend="italic">April 1801.</hi></dateline>
						<p><date>1. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> A</persRef>— a little better, though yet excessively
							weak— I had a bad night, and was not well through the course of this
							day— Walk’d both before and after dinner— Read this Evening the first
							book of <persRef ref="delille-jacques">De lille’s</persRef> homme des
							champs.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-02">
					<head>2 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-02"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>2. </date>Changed my apartment last night. Copying letter to
								<persRef ref="adams-thomas">my brother</persRef>— <persRef
								ref="proby-elizabeth">Lady Carysfort</persRef> called to see
								<persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								Adams</persRef> before dinner— She continues better— Long walk in
							the afternoon.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-03">
					<head>3 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-03"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>3. </date>Weather setting in very fine— Good friday— I went this
							afternoon to the sacred concert at the Opera house— The same performance
							that I heard three years ago— House excessively full, and warm.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-04">
					<head>4 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-04"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>4. </date>At <persRef ref="u">Schickler’s</persRef> Compting house
							this morning— News of the <persRef ref="paul-i">Emperor of
								Russia’s</persRef> death— Enclosed a letter, for the <persRef
								ref="madison-james">Sec<hi rend="superscript">y:</hi> of State</persRef>,
							and one for <persRef ref="adams-thomas">my brother</persRef>, by
								<persRef ref="proby-john">Lord Carysfort’s</persRef> Courier, under
							cover to <persRef ref="king-rufus">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								King</persRef>. Another letter to the former, enclosed to <persRef
								ref="murray-william2">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Murray</persRef>— Walk
							before and after dinner.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-05">
					<head>5 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-05"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>5. </date>Read a sermon of <persRef ref="tillotson-john"
								>Tillotson</persRef>, upon the atonement of Christ. Called this
							afternoon at <persRef ref="proby-john">Lord Carysfort’s</persRef>—
							Evening at <persRef ref="augustusferdinand">Prince
							Ferdinand’s</persRef>— Whist with <persRef ref="u">Baron de
								Hagen</persRef>, <persRef ref="tilly-alexandre">Count
								Tilly</persRef>, and a french gentleman—a stranger. Upon returning
							home, found letters, from <persRef ref="adams-abigail">my
								mother</persRef>, <persRef ref="king-rufus">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								King</persRef>, <persRef ref="murray-william2">Murray</persRef> and
								<persRef ref="pitcairn-joseph">Pitcairn</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-06">
					<head>6 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-06"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>6. </date><persRef ref="proby-elizabeth">Lady Carysfort</persRef>
							called upon <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> Adams</persRef> this forenoon— After dinner we took a
							short walk under the trees—and then called for half an hour at <persRef
								ref="brown-mary">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Brown’s</persRef>— Evening
							at home— Cribbage.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-07">
					<head>7 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-07"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Health and Illness</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>7. </date>Letter to <persRef ref="adams-john">my father</persRef>—
							Gazette N. 1. enclosed to <persRef ref="murray-william2">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>r:</hi> Murray</persRef>.— Rode to Charlottenburg with <persRef
								ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								Adams</persRef>, this afternoon— Call’d at the tents as we return’d—
							Evening at home— Have a bad cold.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-08">
					<head>8 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-08"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>8. </date>Changed my Studying room. Walking this morning, I met
								<persRef ref="proby-john">Lord Carysfort</persRef>, and walk’d with
							him.— News of an attack upon Copenhagen by the English— Said to have
							been unsuccessful— Dined with <persRef ref="kinnaird-charles">Kinnaird</persRef>—
								<persRef ref="brown-charles">D<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
							Brown</persRef>, <persRef ref="garlike-benjamin">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Garlike</persRef>, and <persRef ref="u">M<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Proby</persRef> there— <persRef ref="u"
								>Boreel</persRef> came after dinner— It rain’d in the Evening.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-09">
					<head>9 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-09"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>9. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> A</persRef>— quite unwell— Walk’d before and after
							dinner— Met <persRef ref="proby-john">Lord Carysfort</persRef>, <persRef
								ref="garlike-benjamin">Garlike</persRef>, <persRef ref="u"
									>Proby</persRef>, and <persRef ref="kinnaird-charles">Kinnaird</persRef>. The
							accounts from Copenhagen are in favour of the English— Evening at
							home.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-10">
					<head>10 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-10"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>10. </date>Spent the Evening and supp’d with <persRef
								ref="proby-john">Lord Carysfort</persRef>— A party to the new
								<persRef ref="correa-joseph">Portuguese Minister</persRef> and
								<persRef ref="u">his Lady</persRef>. The Company about sixty
							persons— Play’d chess with <persRef ref="garlike-benjamin"
								>Garlike</persRef>— I stay’d to supper. Home at about 11.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-11">
					<head>11 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-11"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>11. </date>Letters to <persRef ref="adams-thomas">my
								brother</persRef> and to the <persRef ref="madison-james">Secretary
								of State</persRef>, enclosed to <persRef ref="murray-william2">M<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Murray</persRef>— 1. upon the Etat de la
							France à la fin de l’an 8— An hour this forenoon at the Casino— In the
							Evening was at a large party at <persRef ref="voneckardstein-ernst"
								>Baron Eckartstein’s</persRef>— Play’d whist with him, <persRef
								ref="proby-john">Lord Carysfort</persRef>, and a young officer whom
							I knew not. Did not stay to supper.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-12">
					<head>12 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-12"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Health and Illness</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>12. </date>I have this day to offer my humble and devout thanks to
							almighty God, for the birth of <persRef ref="adams-george">a
								son</persRef>, at half-past three o’clock afternoon.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-13">
					<head>13 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-13"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Health and Illness</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>13. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> Adams</persRef> had a very bad night and has been
							excessively ill almost the whole of this day— <persRef
								ref="proby-elizabeth">Lady Carysfort</persRef> called in the
							afternoon. I dined at the <persRef ref="alvensleben-philipp">Minister
								Alvensleben’s</persRef> with a diplomatic company of about forty
							persons— Sent an excuse for the evening to <persRef
								ref="wilhelminaofhesse">Princess Henry’s</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-14">
					<head>14 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-14"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>14. </date>At about one o’clock this morning there was a cry of
							fire— I rose and went out to see where it was. When I got opposite the
							palace, I was informed it was extinguished— Return’d home and went again
							to bed— <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								Adams</persRef> appear’d rather better than yesterday, but several
							times in the course of the day was excessively ill. <persRef
								ref="proby-john">Lord Carysfort</persRef> and <persRef
								ref="garlike-benjamin">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Garlike</persRef>
							called on me this forenoon— <persRef ref="brown-mary">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> Brown</persRef> was here in the afternoon. I took
							short walks before and after dinner.— Wrote a letter to <persRef
								ref="adams-abigail">my mother</persRef>, which I enclosed to
								<persRef ref="pitcairn-joseph">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Pitcairn</persRef>, with press copies of Gazette 1. and 1. upon
							<persRef ref="dlanautte-alexandre">Hauterive’s</persRef>
							book.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-15">
					<head>15 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-15"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Health and Illness</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<pb n="323" type="ms"/>
						<p><date>15. </date><persRef
								ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								Adams</persRef> was extremely ill the whole day. Very dangerously so
							indeed.— I could pay no attention to any-thing else— Took short walks
							before and after dinner— She has taken such an aversion to <persRef
								ref="u">professor Ribke</persRef>, that she would on no account see
							him again.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-16">
					<head>16 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-16"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>16. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> Adams</persRef> is much better, and I hope in a fair
							way of recovery— I dined at <persRef ref="ofarrillyherrera-gonzalo"
									>Gen<hi rend="superscript">l:</hi> O’Farrill’s</persRef>, with a small
							company— The new danish <persRef ref="vonbaudissin-heinrich">Minister
								Count Baudissin</persRef>, and <persRef ref="alfieri-carlo">Count Castel-Alfer</persRef>, the Sardinian
							Minister who has return’d were there.— In the Evening I went to <persRef
								ref="radziwill-anton">Prince Radziwill’s</persRef>, to the plays—
							Saw two French Comedies, Les rivaux d’eux mêmes, and Le Sourd— There was
							yet another, but I did not stay to see it— <persRef ref="brown-mary"
									>M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Brown</persRef> called on M<hi
								rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Adams— Letters from America.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-17">
					<head>17 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-17"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>17. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> Adams</persRef> continued better this day; but had an
							ill turn at night— I Dined at <persRef ref="brown-charles">D<hi
								rend="superscript">r:</hi> Brown’s</persRef>— Only <persRef ref="kinnaird-charles"
								>Kinnaird</persRef> there, besides <persRef
									ref="brown-fanny;brown-margaret;brown-isabella;brown-mary;brown-william5">the
								family</persRef>— Long walk in the Evening— <persRef
								ref="garlike-benjamin">Garlike</persRef> called upon me in the
							forenoon, and brought me the Copenhagen Convention to read.— Brought by
								<persRef ref="u">Captain Doyle</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-18">
					<head>18 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-18"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>18. </date>Letters to the <persRef ref="madison-james">Secretary of
								State</persRef>; to <persRef ref="adams-john">my father</persRef>
							(Gazette 2) and to <persRef ref="johnson-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> Johnson</persRef>, enclosed to <persRef
								ref="pitcairn-joseph">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Pitcairn</persRef>.
							Dined at <persRef ref="proby-john">Lord Carysfort’s</persRef>— <persRef
								ref="brown-charles">D<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Brown</persRef>,
								<persRef ref="u">Captain Doyle</persRef>, <persRef ref="u">Count
								Wengersky</persRef> and <persRef ref="vongentz-friedrich">M<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Gentz</persRef> were there— <persRef
								ref="proby-elizabeth">Lady Carysfort</persRef>, was with <persRef
								ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>—
							this evening— I walk’d under the linden trees with <persRef ref="u">M<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Richard</persRef>— Thunder shower late this
							Evening.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-19">
					<head>19 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-19"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>19. </date>Read a sermon of <persRef ref="tillotson-john">Tillotson</persRef>; upon family worship— Dined
							again at <persRef ref="proby-john">Lord Carysfort’s</persRef>— <persRef
								ref="vonbruhl-karl">Count Brühl’s</persRef>
							<persRef ref="vonbruhl-fanny;bruhl-maria;vonbruhl-sophia"
								>family</persRef>, <persRef ref="deperusse-francois">General
								d’Escars</persRef> and <persRef ref="u">Miss Kehl</persRef> were
							there— After dinner I took a long walk in the park— <persRef
								ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>—
							yet very unwell.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-20">
					<head>20 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-20"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>20. </date>Writing busily to <persRef ref="adams-john">my
								father</persRef>— Ninth day from the birth of <persRef
								ref="adams-george">my child</persRef>— Pass’d the Evening at
								<persRef ref="augustusferdinand">Prince Ferdinand’s</persRef>;
							play’d Casino, with the Prince, <persRef ref="proby-elizabeth">Lady
								Carysfort</persRef> and the young <persRef ref="vonvoss-luise">Countess Voss</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-21">
					<head>21 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-21"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Health and Illness</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>21. </date>Letter to <persRef ref="adams-thomas">my
								brother</persRef> (2. Et. Fr.) enclosed to <persRef ref="king-rufus"
									>M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> King</persRef>, to go by a Courier of
								<persRef ref="proby-john">Lord Carysfort</persRef>— Likewise a
							letter for <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> A</persRef>— to <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> Court</persRef>— She continues to recover though very
							slowly indeed— This day the <hi rend="italic">thrush</hi>, made its
							first appearance upon her <persRef ref="adams-george"
							>child</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-22">
					<head>22 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-22"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>22. </date>I continue writing to <persRef ref="adams-john">my
								father</persRef>— <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi
									rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>— was moved for the first time,
							from her bed room, into the next chamber— <persRef ref="proby-elizabeth"
								>Lady Carysfort</persRef> and <persRef ref="brown-mary">M<hi
									rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Brown</persRef> called to see her— Evening
							at home after walking in the park.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-23">
					<head>23 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-23"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>23. </date><persRef ref="garlike-benjamin">Garlike</persRef> sent
							me the Manuscript of <persRef ref="divernois-francis">Sir Francis
								d’Ivernois’s</persRef> answer to <persRef ref="dlanautte-alexandre"
								>Hauterive</persRef>; which I read. <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> Schickler</persRef> called this afternoon to see
								<persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								A</persRef>— I am writing industriously if not profitably.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-24">
					<head>24 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-24"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>24. </date><persRef ref="garlike-benjamin">Garlike</persRef> called
							on me this forenoon. The weather very fine— I walked in the park in the
							morning, and again towards Evening.— Not very well.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-25">
					<head>25 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-25"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>25. </date>Letter to <persRef ref="adams-john">my father</persRef>
							(2, 3. Et. Fr: copies) enclosed to <persRef ref="murray-william2">M<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Murray</persRef> for <persRef
								ref="bourne-sylvanus">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Bourne</persRef>—
							Evening at <persRef ref="augustusferdinand">Prince
							Ferdinand’s</persRef>— Play’d whist with <persRef ref="u">Baron Münchhausen</persRef>, <persRef
								ref="u">young Dorville</persRef>, and <persRef ref="u">Kornatofsky</persRef>— weather continues
							fine— <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								A</persRef>— not so well as yesterday.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-26">
					<head>26 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-26"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Health and Illness</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>26.— </date>Read prayers— A sermon of <persRef ref="tillotson-john"
								>Tillotson</persRef>. Second upon family religious exercises.— Dined
							at <persRef ref="brown-charles">D<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
							Brown’</persRef>s— Upon coming home found a letter from <persRef
								ref="marshall-john">J Marshall</persRef>—3. Feb<hi rend="superscript"
								>y:</hi> acting as Sec<hi rend="superscript">y:</hi> of State.—enclosing my
							letter of recall, from this court; signed <persRef ref="adams-john">John
								Adams</persRef>, and dated 31. January— Likewise a permission to
							return to the United States— Took a walk in the park— When I came home,
							found <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								A</persRef>— very ill again— She continued excessively ill the whole
							evening.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-27">
					<head>27 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-27"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Health and Illness</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>27. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> Adams</persRef> was dreadfully ill the whole night—
							And owing to my deep concern for her, I had not an hour’s rest— This day
							she has continued weak and helpless to an extreme— It was utterly
							impossible for me to write much this day— I read something of <persRef
								ref="volney-constantin">Volney’s</persRef> travels in Egypt and
							Syria.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-28">
					<head>28 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-28"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Health and Illness</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>28. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> A</persRef>— still confined to her bed, with almost an
							impossibility of moving so much as from one side of it to the other—
							Letters to the <persRef ref="madison-james">Sec<hi rend="superscript">y:</hi> of
								State</persRef>, and to <persRef ref="adams-thomas">my
								brother</persRef> (3. Et: Fr:) enclosed to <persRef
								ref="pitcairn-joseph">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
							Pitcairn</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-29">
					<head>29 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-29"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Health and Illness</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>29. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> A</persRef>— remains immovable from and nearly so in
							her bed; she was the whole day as weak and faint as she has been at any
							period hitherto— <persRef ref="neale-pauline">Pauline Neale</persRef>
							and <persRef ref="brown-mary">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Brown</persRef>
							called to see her this afternoon.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-30">
					<head>30 April 1801</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04-30"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<pb n="324" type="ms"/>
						<p><date>30. </date><persRef
								ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>—
							not quite so ill as she had been for several days before— Spent the
							Evening at <persRef ref="u">Madame de Saldern’s</persRef>— Play’d whist
							with <persRef ref="u">Madame de Heinitz</persRef>, <persRef
								ref="haugwitz-johanna">Countess Haugwitz</persRef>, and the new
							Portuguese Minister <persRef ref="correa-joseph">Chevalier de Correa</persRef>— Home
							soon after nine.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1801-04-xx">
					<head>Day</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1801-04"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Health and Illness</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date><hi rend="italic">Day</hi>.</date> <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi
									rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>—’s illness through the whole of
							this month, has unavoidably broken through the regularity of my
							occupations— My rest has so often been disturbed in the night that I
							could have no constant rising hour; and the extreme anxiety and
							agitation of my mind, has often rendered studious application
							impossible. I have usually risen between 6 and 7. And when I could, have
							pass’d the forenoon, excepting when with M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A— in
							writing letters— Walk’d half an hour— Dined between 3 and 4. Walk’d
							again an hour towards evening, and spent the remainder of it until l0 or
							11. in her chamber.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</body>
	</text>
